            , Esq; sworn.</p>
               <p>The prisoner was my <rs id="t17771203-54-deflabel315" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17771203-54-defend556 t17771203-54-deflabel315"></join>. On last Saturday was fortnight I enquired for him, and found he was gone out of town. I then immediately missed the things mentioned in the indictment. My watch was on the table in the dressing-room. My money and my pocket-book were in my pocket the night before. I saw the prisoner at Sir John Fielding's on the Wednesday following; I recovered my watch and key, but the chain and seal are gone. I have recovered my pocket-book and nine guineas and an half of the money. Sir 
               <persName id="t17771203-54-person560">
                  John
                   Fielding
               <interp inst="t17771203-54-person560" type="surname" value="Fielding"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17771203-54-person560" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17771203-54-person560" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             asked him whether the nine guineas and half were part of the money he took from me? He said, Yes, and he was willing I should have it again.</p>
               <p>[The pocket-book and watch were produced in court, and deposed to by the prosecutor.]</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17771203-54-person561">
